03738nam a22005415i 9780804773522DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047735227 a10.1515/97808047735222doi  a(DE-B1597)563893  a(OCoLC)1178769373  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJS7192.H26 2010 7aPOL0400402bisacsh04a320.8095981 aHadiz, Vedi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLocalising Power in Post-Authoritarian Indonesia :bA Southeast Asia Perspective /cVedi Hadiz. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Issues in Asia and the Pacific00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Localisation and Globalisation -- tChapter One. Decentralisation, Development and Democracy Theoretical Issues and Debates -- tChapter Two. The Post-Authoritarian Context -- tChapter Three. The Localisation of Power and Institutional Change -- tChapter Four. A Political Sociology of Local Elites -- tChapter Five. Money Politics and Thuggery in New Local Democracies -- tChapter Six. The Politics of Inclusion and Exclusion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about how the design of institutional change results in unintended consequences. Many post-authoritarian societies have adopted decentralization-effectively localizing power-as part and parcel of democratization, but also in their efforts to entrench "good governance." Vedi Hadiz shifts the attention to the accompanying tensions and contradictions that define the terms under which the localization of power actually takes place. In the process, he develops a compelling analysis that ties social and institutional change to the outcomes of social conflict in local arenas of power. Using the case of Indonesia, and comparing it with Thailand and the Philippines, Hadiz seeks to understand the seeming puzzle of how local predatory systems of power remain resilient in the face of international and domestic pressures. Forcefully persuasive and characteristically passionate, Hadiz challenges readers while arguing convincingly that local power and politics still matter greatly in our globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDecentralization in governmentzIndonesia. 0aElite (Social sciences)zIndonesia. 0aLocal governmentzIndonesia. 0aPower (Social sciences)zIndonesia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / Local.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477352240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804773522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804773522.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles